<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-103-134 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 023 227</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic News  July 22 1991 v37 n1870 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fear trade accord's costs could boost DRAM prices. (semiconductortrade agreement could increase Japanese suppliers' costs)</TITLE><AUTHOR>McCausland, Richard.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The semiconductor trade agreement, which takes effect Aug 1, 1991,may increase prices of DRAM devices because of the increasedadministrative costs the agreement makes on Japanese suppliers.andO;The agreement requires Japanese semiconductor vendors to recordproduct costs, home market prices and US prices on metal-oxidesemiconductor (MOS) DRAMs, VRAMs and SRAMs, and microprocessors,microcontrollers, application-specific integrated circuits (ASICs)and emitter-coupled logic (ECL) devices.andP;  Japanese companies arestill uncertain about the effect of the data collectionrequirements on prices, but they say prices are likely tofluctuate with the exchange rate and with domestic pricing.andP;  USgovernment sources deny that the agreement will lead to increaseddevice prices and say collection costs will be minimal.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     International tradeJapanese CompetitionPrice IncreasesDRAMSemiconductor industry.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>